04340nam a22006975i 9780674037526DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221995mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740375267 a10.4159/97806740375262doi  a(DE-B1597)571844  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aGN21.G44 ǂb A3 1995eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a301.0921 aGeertz, Clifford, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter the Fact :bTwo Countries, Four Decades, One Anthropologist /cClifford Geertz. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJohn Harvard library00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 Towns -- t2 Countries -- t3 Culture -- t4 Hegemonies -- t5 Disciplines -- t6 Modernities -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Suppose," Clifford Geertz suggests, "having entangled yourself every now and again over four decades or so in the goings-on in two provincial towns, one a Southeast Asian bend in the road, one a North African outpost and passage point, you wished to say something about how those goings-on had changed." A narrative presents itself, a tour of indices and trends, perhaps a memoir? None, however, will suffice, because in forty years more has changed than those two towns--the anthropologist, for instance, anthropology itself, even the intellectual and moral world in which the discipline exists. And so, in looking back on four decades of anthropology in the field, Geertz has created a work that is characteristically unclassifiable, a personal history that is also a retrospective reflection on developments in the human sciences amid political, social, and cultural changes in the world. An elegant summation of one of the most remarkable careers in anthropology, it is at the same time an eloquent statement of the purposes and possibilities of anthropology's interpretive powers. To view his two towns in time, Pare in Indonesia and Sefrou in Morocco, Geertz adopts various perspectives on anthropological research and analysis during the post-colonial period, the Cold War, and the emergence of the new states of Asia and Africa. Throughout, he clarifies his own position on a broad series of issues at once empirical, methodological, theoretical, and personal. The result is a truly original book, one that displays a particular way of practicing the human sciences and thus a particular--and particularly efficacious--view of what these sciences are, have been, and should become."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAnthropologiexPhilosophie. 0aAnthropologistsxBiographyxAsia. 0aAnthropologistsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aAnthropologuesxBiographiesxAsie. 0aAnthropologuesxBiographiesxÉtats-Unis. 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674037526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674037526/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK